As to all the rest he made no edict, but declared that he would stante all bis decreta on the edicta urbana. The provincial edicts maythus perhaps be regarded asin some way serving the purposes which, for the generalisations oi modern social science, are obtained by collections ol statistics in various parts ol the world. The edict oi the praetor peregrinus was a collection of legal rules which were found to be observed in common by all the peoples with whom Rome was acquainted; and the formulation ol such rules would be facilitated, and their number largely increased, bya com· parison oi the various provincial edicts. The institution of the pro· vinces, and, with them, of the edictum provinciale, must have given a great impulse to the development ol the edict os the praetor pere· grinus; through the medium ol the latter they were brought into relation with the edictum urbanum. We do not know whether the work of Ofilius, referred to by Pomponius in Dig. 1. a. a, was an attempt to collect and arrange the various edicta3 but we shall see that when the edict was systematised by Salvius Julianus, in the reign ol Hadrian, he probably incorporated in it some portion os the pro· vincial legislation (see p. 43 inl).
